/*!
\page DriftModelPage The Drift model
	

[TOC]
The model consists in the steam mass balance equation together with the mixture mass conservation, the mixture momentum balance and mixture energy balance equations. The main unknowns are the steam mass concentration \f$c_v\f$, the pressure \f$P\f$, the mixture velocity \f$\vec{u}_m\f$, and the common temperature \f$T\f$. The model uses stiffened gas laws \f$p_g(\rho_g,T)\f$ and  \f$p_l(\rho_l,T)\f$ as well as  linearised internal energy law \f$e_k(T)\f$ valid around the saturation points \f$(P=1 bar, T=373K)\f$ or \f$(P=155 bars, T=618K)\f$ depending on the value of the enum \ref pressureEstimate.

The drift model is a system of four nonlinear equations taking the following conservative form
\f{eqnarray*}
\left\{\begin{array}{lll}
         \partial_t\phi (\alpha_g\rho_g+\alpha_l\rho_l)&+\nabla\cdot\phi(\alpha_g\rho_g{}^t\vec{u}_g+\alpha_l\rho_l{}^t\vec{u}_l)&=0\\
         \partial_t\phi (\alpha_g\rho_g)&+\nabla\cdot\phi(\alpha_g\rho_g{}^t\vec{u}_g)&=\Gamma_g(h_m,\Phi)\\
         \partial_t\phi (\alpha_g\rho_g\vec{u}_g+\alpha_l\rho_l\vec{u}_l)&+\nabla\cdot\phi(\alpha_g\rho_g\vec{u}_g\otimes\vec{u}_g+\alpha_l\rho_l\vec{u}_l\otimes\vec{u}_l)+\phi\vec{\nabla}p&=p\vec{\nabla}\phi+\phi\rho_m\vec{g}-\phi K_g\alpha_g\rho_g||\vec{u}_g||\vec{u}_g-\phi K_l\alpha_l\rho_l||\vec{u}_l||\vec{u}_l\\
         \partial_t\phi (\alpha_g\rho_g E_g+\alpha_l\rho_l E_l)&+\nabla\cdot\phi(\alpha_g\rho_g H_g{}^t\vec{u}_g+\alpha_l\rho_l H_l{}^t\vec{u}_l)&=\Phi+\phi\rho\vec{g}\cdot\vec{u}-\phi K_g\alpha_g\rho_g||\vec{u}_g||^3-\phi K_l\alpha_l\rho_l||\vec{u}_l||^3
        \end{array}\right.,
\f}
where the total energy and total enthalpy are defined by
\f{eqnarray*}
E_k=e_k+\frac{1}{2}|\vec{u}_k|^2&,&\quad H_k=h_k+\frac{1}{2}|\vec{u}_k|^2,\qquad k=v,l,
\f}
where \f$e_k\f$ is the internal energy, and \f$h_k=e_k+\frac{p}{\rho_k}\f$ the enthalpy associated to phase \f$k\f$ and
\f{eqnarray*}
\rho_m&=&\alpha_g\rho_g+\alpha_l\rho_l\\
\vec{u}_m&=&\frac{\alpha_g\rho_g\vec{u}_g+\alpha_l\rho_l\vec{u}_l}{\alpha_g\rho_g+\alpha_l\rho_l}\\
h_m&=&\frac{\alpha_g\rho_g h_g+\alpha_l\rho_l h_l}{\alpha_g\rho_g+\alpha_l\rho_l}.
\f}
We need a drift correlation for the relative velocity:
\f{eqnarray*}
\vec{u}_r=\vec{u}_g-\vec{u}_l=\vec{f}_r(c_g,\vec{u}_m,\rho_m).
\f}
For the moment the only drift correlation available is \f$\vec{u}_g=\vec{u}_l\f$.

The phase change is modeled using the formula
\f{eqnarray*}
 \Gamma_g=\left\{\begin{array}{cc}
         \frac{\Phi}{\mathcal{L}}&\textrm{ if } T^{sat}\leq T \textrm{ and } 0<\alpha_g<1\\[1.5ex]
         0& \textrm{ otherwise }
        \end{array}\right..
\f}
The parameters \f$\lambda_k, \nu_k,\vec g, K_k\f$ and \f$\Phi\f$ can be set by the user.

\f$\phi\f$ is a function of space that can be set by the user. The default value is \f$\phi=1\f$.

* The class : \ref DriftModel implements the 4 equation drift model

* \subpage ExampleDriftModelPage "Here are C and Python example scripts using the Drift Model  "


*/
